I used the exceptional work of bmoshe (www.thingiverse.com/thing:10650) as the base and added the cylinder with the cutouts in Tinkercad so you could drink without hanging your lips on the coozie itself. This is also designed to be printed without support. You will get a tiny droop on the chin and ear tips but it is very minor. One other important tip -- if you print at 100%, it will hold a can through a hurricane! It's tight! Print at 101% for a perfect hold. It won't fall out but you don't have to crush the can to remove it.

This is a marble run that visualizes the Brachistochrone Problem, which was a challenge by Johann Bernoulli to the mathematicians of his day to prove that the direct path between two points is always the fastest.  Supposedly only a hand full of those mathematicians took the time to think of the problem in a real world context - i.e. taking gravity into account.  The importance of the problem today illustrates the need to check our mathematical solutions against real world conditions.

description.text:
This linear axis design avoids steel plain rods and linear bearings/bushings, instead using a lasercut structure with low-cost low-friction tape forming plain bearings.

The I-beam structure makes it very rigid, and trapped-nut pockets for M4 on all sides allows to use it as standard basis for constructing machines, similar to how aluminum profiles are used today.

Quick video demo: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oqJivOp4JyQ

Part of the TapeCore project, https://github.com/jonnor/tapecore
Next tests is to construct the axes out of multiple smaller pieces, to test whether one can build axis longer than the lasercutter. Both for making large machines, and for future self-replication.

For the pulley and idler you can use, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1850661

Vitamins needed:

  • Low-friction tape. UHMW PE or Teflon ideal. Kapton also works OK
  • NEMA17 stepper motor, incl M3 screws
  • Braided line (fishing line or similar)
  • 4 pieces M4x20+
  • 4 pieces M4x15+

Designed for 6mm material (MDF/plywood/acrylic), can be changed in the included FreeCAD source.

I´ve remixed (redesigned from scratch based on the remix source measurements and idea) this cause the original design showed too much of the fan duct and had the nozzle not centered (check https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e4wvldq7f-w for the view - yes I know the camera wasn´t setup up correct). so i redesigned this with another angle and a slightly closer tube to fit my camera better.
See picture above for the new view - the angle was necessary cause otherwise the cable from the camera would be squished in between the left Z carriage and the holder while homing or print on the far left of the bed.

Can anyone recommend a endoscope camera with a stable frame rate and full HD resolution (or is this impossible in this small form factor ?)

UPDATE: Since my camera was not properly fixed - i reduced the diameter by 0,1 mm.

There are two versions now 69 means the diameter for the camera is 6,9mm and 70 means its 7,0mm - if your camera is 7,0mm I´d recommend the 69 version - it will hold the camera better than the other one.

UPDATE: the camera kept falling out and securing with a zip tie isn´t technically correct ;-)
This led to V2 version with integrated locking brackets for M3 screw and nut (I didn´t try printing an M3 thread - but maybe it could be cut). See Photos and stl attached - video of the making (https://youtu.be/Hnqc29BRr1c) and the new angle (soon to come)

UPDATE: Check out the V4 Version - after some hours of recording the camera came loose again so i decided to make a screw to fix it. similar to the first screw version this has two brackets but this time one of the holes is bigger and the other one smaller - so if you use a tapping m3 screw this should work as mine. old files are still here in case you want to tinker around with.

V5 Update: I needed my camera a bit further away from the nozzle to have a better focus (check the blurry videos). V5 provides this - see the 2 pictures of the new view.

description.text:
This thing provides simple and very easy-to-use bed levelling. Loosely based upon ideas presented in thing 62553 ('The Calibrator'), this design uses a Digital Dial Indicator such as this:

https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B01H035DRO/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o09_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Also available from:

http://www.harborfreight.com/1-inch-sae-metric-digital-indicator-93295.html

Note there are a range of prices for these digital indicators - we don't need supreme accuracy so expect to pay in the region of $20-$30.

You can interface the dial indicator via a USB connection according to the following instgructions:

https://hackaday.io/project/511-digital-dial-indicator-cnc-surface-probe

This thing should work on any 3D printer based upon the Makerbot 2 design.

In implementing this thing I now have a very simple means of adjusting bed levelling. No more moving the head around and trying to gauge height by sliding a piece of paper under the nozzle - just set one height point then move this thing around to set the same height across the table. Bed levelling takes just 2 minutes and the result is a bed which is levelled more accurately than using a piece of paper.

In order to create this thing you'll need some extra's:

4x N38 Round Rare Earth Neodymium Magnets 12mm x 3mm With 3mm hole.
20x M3 Flanged Rivnuts (sometimes called 'nutserts').
4x M3 10mm countersunk bolts.
2x M3 20mm bolts.
1x M6 50mm bolt and nut.

If you don't have rivnuts you can print the sled 'with nuts', and use M3 nuts instead. Rivnuts are definitely better though.

ebay is your friend if you need any of the above.

Using the thing is straightforward. Note that we aren't interested in setting a particular height - we just need all points on the bed to be the same height:

1) Set to home position - bed raised, nozzles in north-east corner.
2) Set bed height in one corner using traditional paper-between-nozzle-and-bed method. This gives you the reference height used by all other levellings points.
3) Slide the nozzles to the right (maximum X).
4) Slip this thing onto the rails - it will hold firmly with the rare earth magnets but can be slid on the X axis. Slide indicator over the point set in (2) above.
5) Zero the dial indicator.
6) Move dial indicator over each adjustment screw and wind bed up/down to set zero on the indicator.

That's it! Bed is levelled and you should get perfect prints!

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is an external shell for the Epson 5040UB projector (should also fit the 5040UBe and 6040 models). Similar to a phone case, this allows the projector owner to change the external color of the projector to match a particular room decor if they don't want the standard white color (or if they don't want to spend another $1000 for the black model 6040). I have a home theater room with a dark blue and black color theme, and the white projector definitely stands out (not in a good way), so I decided to design this shell.

It includes holes for the lens, the front vent fans, IR ports, status lights, the rear connector panel, and a door for the side button panel. I also added a number of holes in the sides to help with thermal control and thus far the shell has remained quite cool. Note I have the projector in low power "Eco" mode and hanging from the ceiling, so to be safe if your setup or power mode is different, I recommend monitoring the projector in the first few hours with the shell on to ensure it doesn't overheat.

General instructions:
This case is assembled from 23 separate parts (see exploded view picture) and took about 70 hours total on my Prusa i3 printer and requires almost 2kg of material (note I printed each part one at a time to check printability, so if you print multiple parts at once, the printing time should come down a bit). You'll need a print volume of about 190 x 190 x 190 mm. Most parts can be printed without support, although you will need support for "Front Parts" 1 and 3. I used support for "Side Part 4" mainly for the door hinge features. For the door itself I incorporated a support feature in the STL file (just snap it off). Use some wire or a long screw as the hinge for the door.

I added tabs and slots where needed to help with assembly. The tab fits may be loose or tight depending on your printer, so be sure to have glue and a file handy! I printed in PLA plastic for part dimensional stability.

Assemble the back, top, and sides and then glue together. Then assemble/glue the front parts and match drill this front assembly into the shell and attach with small #4 wood screws. To put it on the projector, you then remove the front assembly with the screws and slide the shell onto the projector from the rear. Then reinstall the front assembly with the screws.

Print in your preferred color, or just paint it.

description.text:
I tried a number of different bowden extruders before i finally sat down and picked all the features I liked from the better ones and amalgamated them in this one that I use on my two Kossels.

This extruder mounts on a 2020 open beam on the Z tower of the Kossel (Delta) and extends to the right side of the printer when viewed from the front.

It's a very strong driving extruder and if there's clicking or skipping, it's probably a problem elsewhere.

Printed .3 layer height, 50% infill, PLA.

Printer:

Kossel

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.3mm

Infill:

50%

Notes:

For the main body of the extruder you shouldn't have to add any supports, there are some in there from Meshmixer and it's all I found was needed.

For the extruder ARM, supports are needed where the bearing will go. I use the default settings in Slic3r for support when printing it. Takes a matter of minutes to chip out the supports.

Steps and Parts

I drill out the filament entry and exit holes in the main extruder body with a 2mm bit. Gives you a little wiggle room to work with.

The filament connector is a 1/8" 27 NPT type since it's far easier to get the bowden tube in and out of in place of those 5mm ones. Plus it makes threading the filament a lot easier (for whatever reason). I use a tap set to pre-thread for the connector.

Bearing is a 625ZZ and held in with a M5 x 20 bolt and nut. Don't over tighten the bolt, the bearing should turn freely without binding.

The knob design is a press fit, but the STL file also has the insert for the ARM. The insert fits inside the arm as a pivot then the arm mounts to the stepper with an M3 x 25. The other stepper mounts use the standard M3 x 6.

Tension is provided by a compression spring. Use a M3 x 25 with washer to retain the spring. The compression spring is 20 x 5 ID, 7.5 OD. eBay labels them as "20mm x 7.5mm x 5mm Alloy Coil Stamping Compression". These springs are fairly stiff so I compress them about 5mm tops.

The hobbed gear is a typical MK8 one. Extend the flat spot on the stepper motor shaft to give the gear something to seat into.

Last is the "guide". I mount the guide 30mm or so above the extruder, it helps keep the somewhat floppy Bowden tube in a better position during printing.

description.text:
Unhappy with your perpendicular Tetrix mounting options (inside C)? Came up with this marvel of technology as a simple solution for mounting channels to one another. The original is the larger version. It only has a single orientation, intended for use with 1.5" 6-32 screws to mount the block to the channel (all the way through with a nut on the end) and then you can use short screws for attaching your other piece of channel. With 4 screws in the bottom and 2 long screws all the way through, i'm unable to budget the connection, so seems pretty robust.

Made the smaller version to see if it would work well enough and print in a fraction of the time. Results were positive on both fronts. Per my extensive testing of screwing two channels together and trying to pull them apart by hand, the short block passed the test just as well as the big block. I only have some fairly short Tetrix channel at my house, so testing with longer channel and more leverage is TBD.

Would love feedback on how much stress these things can take. Planning to add a version with thread in holes on the side for those that don't have 1.5" long screws at hand.

UPDATE: Added an updated contour block with smaller holes on the sides for mounting into. This means using shorter screws that thread into the block instead of longer ones that pass through. We started using these in our robot and found really quick that it was more of a pain to use the long screws (plus we have a bajillion short screws). Enjoy!

title: Rigidbot Power Supply Upgrade - Back plate system

description.text:
This is the back plate mounting system for the 24V 550W ATX style power supply upgrade for an Rigidbot or Rigidbot Big (RB1 or RBB) while still using the original main board.

These back plates provide a common system for mounting the new upgraded power supply and connecting it to the original stock main board through a Kycon adapter on both the Regular and the Big. There are three STL files. The Power Side. the RB1 Main Board Side, and the Middle. The power supply and RB1 board sides work on either size of printer. The middle section is required only for the Big.

Designed to be printed on a 10 X 10 bed so that a regular printer can print its own upgrade. A big can fit all three parts at once. The files are Cura scaled and oriented for printing.

The rest of the kit parts can be found at the link below with additional pictures and instructions. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1712645
NOTE the print and post print instructions below.

Printer:

Rigidbot 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1 - 0.2 mm

Infill:

20% - 22%

Notes:

These are precision fit parts. Use of calibrated filament is strongly recommended for best results. I use the following calibration clips. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1037301

These prints work best on a well leveled flat aluminum bed wiped down with Windex and covered with 3M blue painters tape. I have had no warping or tape peeling up while printing many sets of the previous iteration of these.

At 0.1 layer resolution and 22% fill the parts are very solid and create a very sturdy support system.

A sharp 3/4" chisel with the bevel side down pops the prints off the bed as yo work around the edges at 40C reheat and helps avoid damaging the tape.

Assembly instructions

Use the M3 bolts that come with the printers for assembly if the plate sections. They will self thread in the holes.

The bottom back tubing needs to be removed from the printer and the Anchors from the kit tagged above need to be inserted in the ends where it used to mount. Review the pictures in that post.

Carefully pre-thread an M4 bolt into the 2 holes on the shelf where the main board cover will rest. Mount the board cover base with M4 bolts onto the back plate first but do not tighten it all the way down. Attach the back plate assembly to the back of the printer. Again do not tighten all the way down. Mount the board cover base plate on the side rail and square it up. Now tighten down all the bolts. Place the main board in its cover and position the top cover and tighten the bolts. Mount the power supply onto its back plate. Plug the Kycon connector into the main board and snap the 4 Pin connection into the key on the back plate. The 4 Pin plug from the power supply will plug into the back on the other side. Insert the feet into the bottom of the Printer. Your power supply upgrade is now complete.

The Kycon adapter and jumper can later be removed allowing you to plug the power supply directly into an upgraded 4E3D main board. See http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1712645 as referenced above for details. You can print the main board part from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1841137 and it will mount on either printer design.

The assembly is quite strong and very solid when mounted on the printer back. The M4 bolts that are used for mounting the stock back cover are still used to mount these plates.

description.text:
The FERMIAC is a mechanical computer from the 1940's which was used to run monte carlo simulations of neutron transport inside nuclear reactors. I want to build one.

You can find full information at my hackaday.io project page.

More updated versions of these files may be available on my github page.

Printer Brand:

Type A Machines

Printer:

2014 Series 1

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.4

Notes:

Wheels, thumbscrew and pt 2 of both drums were printed with ~20% infill.

Pt 1 of both drums was printed with 0% infill and 3 layer walls, this was required on my printer to get the thin wall at the top of each part to form.

I used PLA at 220C with a glass heated bed at 70C, no additional adhesion. Minor cleaning was required to remove stray plastic from the shaft holes and bearing pockets.

Assembly

Additional required parts:

  • 8x M3x12 bolts
  • 1x M3x16 bolt
  • 4x M3x6 bolts
  • 13x M3 nuts
  • 4x M3 washers
  • 2x 91mm M3 or 3/16" smooth rod
  • 2x 97.5mm M3 or 3/16" smooth rod
  • 2x ~110mm lengths of thin wire
  • 6x ~1" OD O-rings to fit drum & wheel grooves
  • Glue
  • Tape

Assembly instructions

  1. Affix both acrylic parts to side panels with medium bolts, see orientation from DXF.
  2. Glue wide strut with center hole to front position of side panels, attach thumbscrew through center hole with long bolt and nut.
  3. Glue drums pt 1 and pt 2.
  4. Install drums into frame (see DXF for orientation), slide short smooth rods through side panel holes to pin. Use tape on side panel to secure rod.
  5. Affix arms to side panel with medium bolts. Glue arm struts. See DXF for orientation.
  6. Install wheels into arms (see DXF for orientation), slide long smooth rods through arm holes to pin. Use tape on arms to secure rod.
  7. Thread washers and short bolts through holes at tip of arms and affix. Wrap thin wire around bolt and tighten to hold read-line in place.

This design was made possible by the Bradbury Science Museum in Los Alamos as well as Fabrizio Coccetti, senior research technologist at the Enrico Fermi center in Rome.

The following two papers were consulted during development:

  • http://www.sif.it/riviste/ncc/econtents/2016/039/02/article/24
  • http://static.sif.it/SIF/resources/public/files/congr15/mc/Coccetti.pdf

description.text:
magnetic phone holder inspired by the great mounting constructed by undergroundsurf

I already had a magnetic phone holder (google/amazon: Automobio) in the A3 P8, but soon the ventilation mounting ripped out the plastic air guide.

This is an as much simplified construction as possible. If you slide out the mobile, just push it down.
The back of the mobile needs of course a small steel plate too. The easiest way it to put a thin steel plate between you may used mobile cover and the phone itself.

I mounted the Automobio magnet holder with a M3x6mm Allen key screw.

You can build the magnet holder yourself by remixing the construction (STEP file also att.) and integrate 3-4 Neodym magnets you can find on eBay. Use a steel plate behind the magnets to increase the holding force. Then put on some sticky silicon sheet/tape (i.e. rescue tape) to avoid having the mobile slip down from the magnets.

description.text:
Hey there!

I found this nice Wooden Chair here on Thingiverse.

The original author, Tommy Kong, made a mess with this model: the top part wasn't manifold at all and it was impossible to print (check here by yourself if you don't believe me :3).

So i decided to fix it by myself and to share with all of you!

This is not a particularly hard print, i uploaded 2 version of the same object, one with the full chair to print with supports and another with 2 individual parts to assemble post-print.

The model in not 100% accurate to a real MAMMUT chair by IKEA but in this way you will have a less stressful time printing this :)

Have a nice print!

So, if you want a solid toy, print the Full version!

title: Feiyu Tech Mini 3D Gimbal Motor Mount / Arm Cover / Shell

description.text:
6 months after purchasing my Feiyu Tech Mini 3D Gimbal I broke the plastic motor mount / shell piece on the arm. This was frustrating as it rendered it useless. On contacting Feiyu Tech they could only offer a repair service if I sent the Gimbal to China and would not offer to sell me a replacement part.

So I decided to model and print one myself. For all you out there in the same position here's a free model that I created which you can use to print a replacement part (I would have been happy to purchase a replacement part, their loss!).

Print with Solid Infill on a slowish speed for best results. You will need 2x M2 hex head nuts which seat into the cutouts inside the part for the arm screws to secure in to. The screw holes for the circuit board and the other half of the cover are designed to be self tapping, just gently screw the M2 screws in and check they fit (dont over tighten or it will strip the hole).

NOTE: You may need to run a 4mm drill bit to ream the 3x countersink screw holes which hold the motor as I forgot to add some tolerance into the print for clearance of the screw heads. I will update for V2 when I get a chance.

Took the Rabbit Habbit and used it in a workshop at 3d.startupweekend.org teaching the ease of mashability.
We created a crippled version of the rabbit and put it in a wheel chair. Thanks @siddiquiahmed and the rest of the class for creating this object!

PegStats is a system to help students explore statistical concepts.  The pegs contain numbers on the surface.  The distribution of the numbers on the pegs is set by what you print.  The students can draw pegs from the set you printed and create easy histograms of the population by sliding the pegs into the included tray.  PegStats can be used from elementary school through college.  Obviously histograms are easily taught, but it also works for bimodal populations, the effects of filtering, and the inadequacies of mean to describe a population.  Even ANOVA can be used on the populations.  The students can also use the numbers on the pegs (recording them as they select them) to perform statistical calculations from mean through proving the distribution is normal.   I've included a PDF file (PegStats Details) with some lesson ideas.  This math manipulative actually mimics an activity I did in my first college chemical engineering lab (we used resistors instead of pegs) so the learners can scale to quite an advanced level.   
Using the Power of 3D printing, the Customizer can be used to make  trays which go higher than 8 if your printer bed is large enough.  The enclosed OpenScad file can be used to make distributions with averages from -9 to 99 (or more if want to change the font size).

Print a tray to create the histograms.  You can use a low fill since it has plenty of strength from the walls.  Pick a peg distribution set.  They are labeled as such "a" is the average and "s" is the standard distribution.  All the sets are designed not to go below 1 or over 8.  The averages and standard deviations are exact for the printed populations (obviously for sub populations of these may vary).  The full details of the distributions is on the enclosed lesson ideas sheet.  If you want to get fancy, pause the print a few layers before the end and change the filament color.  This makes the numbers easier to read and makes the levels on the histogram clearer.  
The prints are relatively big, but they are simple.  No support is needed and there is plenty of contact with the bed so nothing should move around.  I printed mine with a 0.4mm nozzle and 0.3mm layer height.  They all fit on my 120mm x 120mm bed.  
If you want a bigger or smaller tray use the customizer tied to this thing.  The customerizer also have an option to leave the numbers off the tray.  This allows you to print several trays and hook them together to cover wide ranges of numbers.  The OpenScad file for peg sets is also included if you want to make your own populations.  I tried to make it available via the customerizer, but it appears the customizer doesn't do random numbers correctly, so you'll have to run it on your own in OpenScad.  There is also a set of blank pegs if you just want to write numbers on the pegs.  
(Please excuse the ridges on everything, I discovered after printing this my base wasn't secured well and was wobbling a bit during the print)

1 x PC PSU ~350-400W good one or 500W cheap;
Other stuff on the pictures.
Added .dwg(AutoCad 2013+) file for some MDF and 1 mm steel laser cutting.
You can make Tool plate and clamps for Your motor(Dremel, laser, etc.)

Springs and cable ties are because the motor is almost 0,5 kg. Work area 100x100 mm. Flashed with GRBL. I am using Grbl Controller. Still learning Inkscape to create files for it.

Thing is final, will not make any changes.

20.11.2016
Made and added clamps for 44mm diameter motor and distance between central holes - 30 mm. And while making the brackets I saw, that my motor is 48 mm, instead of 51 mm diameter. So this is corrected in the description.

13.04.2017
Finally I have got some time to test it and found 2 things to correct:

  1. 018_Vice_Clamp.stl - lower the allowances for the nut in it by 0.2 mm on each side. I have printed it with 0.3 mm nozzle and it was very loose in its bed. If You printed with 0.4 mm and it is fine in Your print - there is no need to print it again;
  2. 016_Vice_Base_A.stl - Did not saw at first, that the counter self securing nut will not rotate - the place for it is too tight. Made it wider +1mm on left and right directions, so now it should be fine. You have to print it again, if already did it or cut a mm on left and right of the nut 'bed'. Also added 2 cuts to indicate 0, 0 (XY), when holding blocks with clamp at the back of the vice.

For milling I am using Freemill - easy to use, but slow making. Then Candle - it is ex GRBL Controll(not grbl controller - these are 2 different softwares). For cut type jobs - Inkscape and then Candle.

title: Prusa i3 mk2 Spool Holder & Filament Guide

description.text:
The original design spool holder works well - but with some rolls i couldn't get it to work without the risk of the roll falling off.
So i designed this one from the measurements I took of the frame and the original holder.

The fit between the bar and the sides is pretty good - the printer did an awesome job: the squares are 10x10mm in fusion 360 - measured after the print: 10x10mm with play of 0.01-0.06mm - this is what I call accurate.

The bar fits quite strong on the sides - but after some uses it will get easier to remove it. The surface could take some finishing with epoxy to be smoother so that the rolls will roll easier on it - or you just leave it and wait till the wear out by themselves.

UPDATE: I didn´t want my 2.3 kg Spools (around 5 pounds) to sit on top of the printer frame. They also needed a bar with like 140mm.
Solution: Make two side pieces with two bottombars to keep it standing and use a longer top bar for the spool.

As those are all from the same simple values you can make a bunch and adjust to your needs. For larger Spools you can use the mounting on top of the printer and the longer bar (140mm) or make two side pieces and use the 80mm bars for a narrow free standing version - or use the free standing version for the big boy spools.

For the Fun I made a filament guide too - didn´t print this yet cause I´m busy printing the filament holder sides - be aware that this will be "disintegrated" when calibrating Z and printing thing very high.
